author: PerspectiveFew7772
body: Had a guy from analog devices, used to be linear tech :( come to my work today and I asked him about the chip shortage and he thinks that once everyone is caught up it will collapse for a bit. Basically because everyone is buying everything they can get their hands on right now(my company included). I'm still bullish on semi's but it's making me rethink my largest holding(SOXX), it's my largest holding by far.

author: Ubiquitous_Prick
body: My Synopsys of this is that I need to Keepsight a Sharps eye on my Target if I expect my Analog Devices to perform.  I can't be a Lazboy and PaySafe my Krispy Kreme if I expect to get Joyy from my BJ's. Is it Farfetch-ed to believe that a CleanSpark of Applied Materials can create some Ammo for some Milestone Ideanomics.

author: idoescompooters
body: Yeah if you compare it to $ADI's dividend then it doesn't look as nice, but when you look at what industries the companies are actually in you find that TSM looks more attractive since they provide wafers whereas Analog Devices isn't so much benefitting from the automotive industry (small percentage from Maxim when the deal goes through).

author: GigaChadEnergy
body:
> Xilinx (NASDAQ:XLNX) shares rose 5% in premarket trading after China approved Analog Devices (NASDAQ:ADI) planned purchase of Maxim Integrated (NASDAQ:MXIM) as investors await China OK for AMD's purchase of Xilinx (XLNX). AMD (NASDAQ:AMD) rose 0.5%.

Great news ADI shareholders as China OKs their merger but also this indicates that AMDs acquisitions will likely get approved too. Wise move on China's part overall to allow these acquisitions instead of being spiteful and blocking. Still, I don't think Nvidia will get approved. Too much is at stake.

body:
Also from the other link those purchases were in Q2 so happened before the continued drop. They are now in losing positions on BABA. They are probably also very sad they cut holdings in PANW as it has done very well lately.

Generation Investment Management materially raised its investment in Alibaba Group Holding (ticker: BABA), initiated a stake in Intel (INTC), and cut holdings in Analog Devices (ADI) and Palo Alto Networks (PANW) in the **second quarter.** The firm disclosed the stock trades, among others, in a form it filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
